January 13, 1971) is an American inventor, entrepreneur, and Republican politician who has been the [[United States Representative]] for [[Kentucky's 4th congressional district]] since 2012.\n\nIn 2012, he defeated Bill Adkins in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Kentucky, 2012|special]] and general elections to represent Northern Kentucky in Washington, D.C. Before joining congress, Massie was [[Judge/Executive|Judge-Executive]] of [[Lewis County, Kentucky|Lewis County]], [[Kentucky]], from 2011 to 2012.  He also ran a start-up company based in [[Massachusetts]], where he previously studied robotics at [[MIT]].  He is an engineer by practice and education.<ref>{{cite web|title=From MIT Entrepreneur to Tea Party Leader: The Thomas Massie Story|url=https://www.xconomy.com/boston/2012/05/17/from-mit-entrepreneur-to-tea-party-leader-the-thomas-massie-story/|website=Xconomy|date=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nMassie has been described as a [[libertarian Republican]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Curry|first1=Tom|title=Libertarian GOP Member Sees Drone Privacy Risk|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/the-container/libertarian-gop-member-sees-drone-privacy-risk/|website=blogs.rollcall.com|accessdate=February 14, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214235304/http://blogs.rollcall.com/the-container/libertarian-gop-member-sees-drone-privacy-risk/|archivedate=February 14, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and is associated with the House [[Liberty Caucus]].\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nThomas Massie was born in [[Huntington, West Virginia]]. He grew up in [[Vanceburg, Kentucky|Vanceburg]], [[Kentucky]], and met his future wife, Rhonda. He earned a bachelor's degree in [[electrical engineering]] and a master's degree in [[mechanical engineering]] from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=MITlem00/>\n\nIn 1993, at MIT, he and his wife started a company called SensAble Devices Inc.<ref name=money00>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1996/07/08/214355/index.htm |title=Sensable Technologies Tactile Computer Interfaces |publisher=CNN |accessdate=January 14, 2012 |date=July 8, 1996 |last=Stipp |first=David}}</ref><ref name=\"nky\"/> Massie was the winner in 1995 of the $30,000 [[Lemelson-MIT Prize|Lemelson-MIT Student Prize]] for inventors.<ref name=MITlem00>{{cite web |url=http://lemelson.mit.edu/winners/thomas-massie |title=Thomas Massie {{!}} Lemelson-MIT Program |accessdate=April 21, 2018 |work=lemelson.mit.edu}}</ref> The company was re-incorporated as SensAble Technologies, Inc., in 1996 after partner Bill Aulet joined the company.<ref name=money00 /> They raised $32 million of [[venture capital]], had 24 different patents, and 70 other employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thomasmassie.com/about/ |title=About &#124; Thomas Massie for US Congress \u2013 4th District Kentucky |publisher=Thomasmassie.com |accessdate=December 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMassie sold the company, and he and his wife moved back to their hometown in [[Lewis County, Kentucky|Lewis County]]. They raised their children on a farm,<ref name=\"nky\"/><ref>{{cite web |author=01/10/12 at 4:27pm by Scott Wartman &nbsp; Comments |url=http://cincinnati.com/blogs/nkypolitics/2012/01/10/thomas-massie-joins-race-for-geoff-davis-congressional-seat/ |title=Thomas Massie joins race for Geoff Davis' Congressional seat &#124; Kentucky Politics |publisher=Cincinnati.com |date= |accessdate=December 21, 2012}}</ref> where he built his own [[off-the-grid]] [[Timber framing|timberframe]] house.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://massiehouse.blogspot.com/|title=Massie House|accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Lewis County Judge Executive==\nIn 2010, Massie pursued the office of [[Judge Executive]] of Lewis County, in order to fight what he considered wasteful spending and intrusion into the lives of the county's citizens by the government.<ref name=\"nky\">{{cite web |url=http://cincinnati.com/blogs/nkypolitics/2012/01/13/massie-courts-tea-party/ |title=Massie courts Tea Party |accessdate=January 14, 2012 |date=January 13, 2012 |publisher=Cincinnati.com |last=Wartman |first=Scott}}</ref> Massie won the primary election, defeating the incumbent by a large margin,<ref name=\"nky\"/> and went on to defeat his Democratic opponent by nearly 40 points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maysville-online.com/news/local/article_80ba9d94-e6fc-11df-a672-001cc4c03286.html |title=Voter turnout exceeds expectations in Lewis County |publisher=Maysville Online |accessdate=January 14, 2012 |date=November 2, 2010 |last=Maynard |first=Misty}}</ref> Massie also campaigned for then-U.S. Senate candidate [[Rand Paul]], speaking to various [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] groups on his behalf.<ref name=\"nky\"/>\n\nMassie resigned as Lewis County Judge-Executive, effective June 30, 2012.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2012 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Kentucky, 2012#District 4}}\n[[File:Kentucky Republican 4th Congressional District Primary Election Results by County, 2012.svg|right|thumb|Results of the primary by county. Red indicates a county won by Massie, green by Webb-Edgington. Gray indicates a county that is not within the 4th congressional district.]]\nIn December 2011, Congressman [[Geoff Davis]] announced his decision to retire from his seat in [[Kentucky's 4th congressional district]]. Massie announced his decision to join the race on January 10, 2012.<ref name=\"ap\">{{cite news |title=Republican Thomas Massie seeks to replace US Rep. Geoff Davis in Kentucky's 4th District |first=Roger |last=Alford |url=http://www.therepublic.com/view/story/def4ddc94bd542ca92d6141b0c9c7dd8/KY--Kentucky-Congress/ |agency=Associated Press |date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=November 14, 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> Massie was endorsed by Senator Rand Paul of Kentucky,<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller |first=Joshua |url=http://atr.rollcall.com/kentucky-rand-paul-backs-massie-in-race-to-succeed-davis/ |title=Kentucky: Rand Paul Backs Thomas Massie in Race to Succeed Geoff Davis |publisher=[[Roll Call]] |date=May 10, 2012 |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://reason.com/blog/2012/05/16/rand-paul-endorses-kentuckys-thomas-mass |title=Rand Paul Endorses Kentucky's Thomas Massie |last=Riggs |first=Mike |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |date=May 16, 2012 |publisher=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref> and Rand's father, Texas Congressman [[Ron Paul]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.usatoday.net/dist/custom/gci/InsidePage.aspx?cId=courier-journal&sParam=39031651.story |title=Ron Paul endorses Massie in 4th District race |accessdate=April 19, 2012 |date=April 13, 2012 |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0412/74940_Page2.html |title=Ron Paul's baby boom |publisher=[[Politico]] |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |date=April 9, 2012 |last=Isenstadt |first=Alex}}</ref> He also received endorsements from [[FreedomWorks]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.freedomworksforamerica.org/candidate/thomas-massie |title=Thomas Massie \u2013 FreedomWorks for America |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |publisher=FreedomWorks}}</ref> [[Club for Growth]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clubforgrowth.org/endorsedcandidates/?subsec=0&id=1072 |title=CFG PAC endorses Thomas Massie in Kentucky |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |publisher=Club for Growth |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505023028/http://www.clubforgrowth.org/endorsedcandidates/?subsec=0&id=1072 |archivedate=May 5, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wfpl.org/2012/05/01/national-club-for-growth-endorses-massie-in-fourth-congressional-district-primary/ |title=National Club For Growth Endorses Massie in Fourth Congressional District Primary |publisher=WFPL |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |date=May 1, 2012 |last=Colston |first=Kenny }}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> [[Gun Owners of America]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goapvf.org/GOA-PVF-2012-Favorites/massieforcongres.htm |title=Thomas Massie: Second Amendment Leadership |publisher=Gun Owners of America |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |last=Macy |first=Tim |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810195130/http://www.goapvf.org/GOA-PVF-2012-Favorites/massieforcongres.htm |archivedate=August 10, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Young Americans for Liberty]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yaliberty.org/pac/candidates/massie |title=Support Thomas Massie \u2013 Young Americans for Liberty |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |publisher=Young Americans for Liberty |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526011619/http://www.yaliberty.org/pac/candidates/massie |archivedate=May 26, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn May 22, 2012, Thomas Massie was elected as the Republican nominee for the 4th congressional district, beating his closest opponents, State Representative [[Alecia Webb-Edgington]] and [[Boone County, Kentucky|Boone County]] Judge Executive Gary Moore, by a double-digit margin.<ref name=\"win\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20120522/NEWS0106/305210092/Tea-party-massie-kentucky |title=Tea party-backed Thomas Massie gets nod in U.S. House 4th District race |publisher=Courier Journal |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |date=May 22, 2012 |last=Gerth |first=Joe}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Massie wins Republican primary for Fourth District |url=http://www.maysville-online.com/news/local/massie-wins-republican-primary-for-fourth-district/article_ebb29f7e-15b7-5e37-af76-66a4ad632807.html |publisher=The Ledger Independent |accessdate=May 23, 2012 |date=May 22, 2012}}</ref> In his victory speech, Massie thanked \"the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]], the liberty movement, and grassroots [[Ronald Reagan]] Republicans.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wlwt.com/Massie-Adkins-To-Compete-For-4th-District-Seat/-/9838586/14519000/-/12k6w9/-/index.html |title=Massie, Adkins To Compete For 4th District Seat |publisher=[[WLWT-TV]] |date=May 22, 2012 |accessdate=July 24, 2012 |agency=Associated Press |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004214106/http://www.wlwt.com/Massie-Adkins-To-Compete-For-4th-District-Seat/-/9838586/14519000/-/12k6w9/-/index.html |archivedate=October 4, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Massie was challenged by Democrat [[Bill Adkins]] in the general election, and was expected to win the election by a wide margin.<ref name=\"win\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0512/76657.html |title=House incumbents win in Kentucky, Arkansas |last=|publisher=[[Politico]] |accessdate=May 23, 2012 |date=May 23, 2012}}</ref> Massie resigned as Lewis County Judge-Executive, effective June 30, 2012, in order to focus on his campaign for U.S. Congress, and allow an election to be immediately held in order to replace him.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bgdailynews.com/news/state/massie-resigns-as-lewis-county-judge-executive/article_8e50201d-6e2e-5e7f-8959-3856f1e1ffc6.html |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120707202348/http://www.bgdailynews.com/news/state/massie-resigns-as-lewis-county-judge-executive/article_8e50201d-6e2e-5e7f-8959-3856f1e1ffc6.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=July 7, 2012 |title=Massie resigns as Lewis County judge-executive |publisher=[[Bowling Green Daily News]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=July 7, 2012 |date=June 29, 2012 }}</ref> He was succeeded by Deputy Lewis County Judge-Executive John Patrick Collins, who was appointed temporarily by Governor [[Steve Beshear]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20120719/NEWS01/307190081/Deputy-Judge-John-Patrick-Collins-replaces-Thomas-Massie-Lewis-County?nclick_check=1 |title=Deputy Judge John Patrick Collins replaces Thomas Massie in Lewis County |publisher=Courier Journal |accessdate=July 20, 2012 |date=July 19, 2012 }}</ref> On July 31, 2012, Congressman Geoff Davis resigned from office, citing a family health issue for his abrupt departure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/on-congress/2012/07/rep-geoff-davis-resigns-from-congress-130702.html |title=Rep. Geoff Davis resigns from Congress |publisher=Politico |accessdate=August 2, 2012 |date=July 31, 2012 |last=Min Kim |first=Seung}}</ref> On August 1, 2012, the Republican Party committee for Kentucky's 4th Congressional district voted unanimously to endorse Massie as the party's nominee once a special election was called.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mycn2.com/politics/gop-committee-backs-massie-for-nomination-in-yet-to-be-called-special-election |title=GOP committee backs Massie for nomination in yet-to-be-called special election |publisher=Pure Politics |accessdate=August 2, 2012 |date=August 1, 2012 |last=Alessi |first=Ryan}}</ref>   A special election was called by Governor [[Steve Beshear]] to take place on the same day as the general election, November 6, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://atr.rollcall.com/breaking-geoff-davis-resigns-from-congress/ |title=Breaking: Geoff Davis Resigns From Congress |publisher=Roll Call |accessdate=August 2, 2012 |date=July 31, 2012 |last=Miller |first=Joshua}}</ref>  This meant that Massie would be running in two separate elections on the same day\u2014one for the right to serve the final two months of Davis' term, another for a full two-year term.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wsaz.com/news/politics/headlines/US-Rep-Geoff-Davis-Resigns-from-Congress-164514256.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130209191946/http://www.wsaz.com/news/politics/headlines/US-Rep-Geoff-Davis-Resigns-from-Congress-164514256.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=February 9, 2013 |title=Special Election Set for U.S. Congressional Seat in Ky |publisher=Newschannel WSAZ-3 |accessdate=September 12, 2012 |date=August 17, 2012 |last=Associated Press |first= }}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2012, Massie won both the general and special elections, defeating his opponent by a wide margin in both elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kypost.com/dpps/news/local_news/Massie-wins-in-Kys-4th-congressional-district_7989435 |title=Massie wins in Ky.'s 4th congressional district |publisher=[[Kentucky Post]] |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |date=November 6, 2012 |last=Osborne |first=Kevin}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Thomas Massie ceremonial swearing-in 2012-11-13.jpg|right|thumb|Massie being sworn into office by Speaker of the House [[John Boehner]] on November 13, 2012.]]\n[[File:Thomas Massie (9912282126).jpg|thumb|Massie speaking at the 2013 [[Liberty Political Action Conference]] (LPAC)]]\nMassie was sworn into office immediately after the election, on November 13, 2012, filling the vacancy left by Geoff Davis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mycn2.com/politics/congressman-elect-massie-says-he-wants-to-see-federal-spending-cuts-take-effect |title=Congressman-elect Massie says he wants to see federal spending cuts take effect |last=Pitts |first=Jacqueline |publisher=Pure Politics |accessdate=November 18, 2012|date=November 9, 2012}}</ref> Massie was selected to serve on three committees, including the [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]], [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]] and [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://massie.house.gov/press-release/us-representative-thomas-massie-selected-several-key-house-committees |title=U.S. Representative Thomas Massie Selected for Several Key House Committees |publisher=Office of Congressman Thomas Massie |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> He was also selected to become Chairman of the [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Technology and Innovation|Subcommittee on Technology and Innovation]], replacing outgoing Chairman [[Ben Quayle]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://massie.house.gov/press-release/us-representative-massie-selected-chairman-technology-subcommittee |title=U.S. Representative Massie Selected as Chairman of Technology Subcommittee |publisher=Office of Congressman Thomas Massie |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |date=January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMassie voted against the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2013]], otherwise known as the [[National Defense Authorization Act|NDAA]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://massie.house.gov/press-release/us-representative-massie-votes-%E2%80%98nay%E2%80%99-ndaa |title=U.S. Representative Massie Votes 'Nay' on NDAA |date=December 21, 2012 |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |publisher=Office of Congressman Thomas Massie}}</ref> and co-sponsored legislation in favor of [[industrial hemp]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://massie.house.gov/press-release/us-representative-massie-signs-industrial-hemp-bill |title=U.S. Representative Massie Signs on to Industrial Hemp Bill |publisher=Office of Congressman Thomas Massie |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |date=November 28, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130220210606/http://massie.house.gov/press-release/us-representative-massie-signs-industrial-hemp-bill |archivedate=February 20, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and repealing federal [[Gun-Free School Zones Act of 1990|gun free zones]] in schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://massie.house.gov/press-release/press-release-us-representative-massie-proposes-repeal-federal-gun-free-school-zones |title=PRESS RELEASE: U.S. Representative Massie Proposes Repeal of Federal Gun Free School Zones Act |publisher=Office of Congressman Thomas Massie |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |date=January 4, 2013}}</ref> Massie voted against the [[fiscal cliff]] deal, saying \"This plan is Washington kicking the can down the road {{interp|...}} The modest spending cuts agreed to in the 2011 debt ceiling deal are postponed by this bill. This bill does nothing to reform our bloated tax code \u2014 in fact the bill perpetuates Obama's failed stimulus spending within the tax code. Finally, it fails to address entitlement reform or the solvency of [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] and [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]].\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://massie.house.gov/press-release/press-release-us-representative-massie-votes-no-fiscal-cliff-deal |title=Press Release: U.S. Representative Massie Votes No on Fiscal Cliff Deal |publisher=Office of Congressman Thomas Massie |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |date=January 2, 2013}}</ref> Massie was the sole member of the House to vote \"present\" on the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action]] of Iran's nuclear agreement, citing constitutional concerns that the treaties are not ratified by the House of Representatives and that he had no authority to vote for or against the nuclear deal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2015/09/11/massie-alone-voting-present-iran-deal/72076938/|title=Massie alone in voting 'present' on Iran deal|date=September 11, 2015|work=Cincinnati.com}}</ref><ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2015/roll493.xml</ref>\n\nMassie broke from the majority of his party by opposing the reelection of [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[John Boehner]], instead casting his vote for Republican Congressman [[Justin Amash]] of Michigan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reason.com/blog/2013/01/03/boehner-re-elected-house-speaker-but-los |title=Boehner Re-Elected House Speaker, But Loses Amash, Some Other Liberty-Leaning Support |last=Doherty |first=Brian | authorlink = Brian Doherty (journalist)|work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |date=January 3, 2013}}</ref> In May 2013, he voted against the [[Stolen Valor Act of 2013]], which passed 390 to 3.<ref name=\"deirdreshesgreen,usatoday\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2014/06/15/congressman-thinks-answer/10565771/|title=A congressman thinks 'no' is the answer|author=Deirdre Shesgreen, USAToday|date=June 15, 2014|work=Cincinnati.com}}</ref>  In December 2013, he was the only congressman to vote against the [[Undetectable Firearms Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wfpl.org/kentucky-congressman-thomas-massie-objects-plastic-gun-ban/|title=Kentucky Congressman Thomas Massie Objects to Plastic Gun Ban|work=89.3 WFPL}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, Massie voted against a bill to name [[Israel]] an American strategic partner. Massie voted no because this bill would have subsidized green energy companies in Israel. He said he would not support subsidies for American green energy companies, let alone foreign ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2014/06/15/congressman-thinks-answer/10565771/|title=A congressman thinks 'no' is the answer|date=June 15, 2014|work=Cincinnati.com}}</ref> However, the bill passed by a margin of 410-to-1.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21610312-pummelling-gaza-has-cost-israel-sympathy-not-just-europe-also-among-americans Israel and the world: Us and them], economist.com.</ref>  In May 2014, Massie objected to a [[voice vote]] to award golf star [[Jack Nicklaus]] a gold medal recognizing his \"service to the nation\", and demanded a [[roll call vote]].<ref name=\"deirdreshesgreen,usatoday\"/> The vote passed easily, 371 to 10.<ref name=\"deirdreshesgreen,usatoday\"/> Through mid-June 2014, Massie had voted \"no\" at least 324 times in the 113th Congress \u2013 opposing  one of every three measures that came to the House floor. ''[[Politico]]'' named him \"Mr. No\".<ref name=\"deirdreshesgreen,usatoday\"/> In November 2016, Massie voted against an extension of [[U.S. sanctions against Iran]], the only member of the House to do so.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=House votes to extend Iran sanctions |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/306205-house-votes-to-extend-iran-sanctions|website=The Hill|publisher=Capitol Hill Publishing Corp|accessdate=December 2, 2016|date=November 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMassie identifies himself as a [[Constitutionalism|constitutional]] [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]. He believes in [[intellectual property]] and thinks it is necessary for incentivizing innovation. Massie has remarked that this is one of the areas in which he does not identify as [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]].<ref>[http://news.sciencemag.org/2012/11/meet-representative-thomas-massie-constitutional-conservative-mit-pedigree Meet Representative Thomas Massie: A Constitutional Conservative With an MIT Pedigree], Science insider</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Massie introduced a one-page bill that would abolish the [[United States Department of Education]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/318310-gop-lawmaker-proposes-abolishing-department-of-education|title=GOP lawmaker proposes abolishing Department of Education|last=Marcos|first=Cristina|date=2017-02-07|work=TheHill|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref> and cosponsored a bill that would abolish the [[Environmental Protection Agency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/861/cosponsors|title=H.R.861 - To terminate the Environmental Protection Agency.|last=|first=|date=|website=Congress.gov|access-date=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2017, in a [[CNN]] interview with [[Kate Bolduan]], Massie expressed skepticism over the role of [[Syria]]n president [[Bashar al-Assad]] in the [[2017 Khan Shaykhun chemical attack]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/05/politics/thomas-massie-syria-attack-not-assad/index.html|title=Congressman: 'I don't think' Assad is behind Syria attack|last=Mueller|first=Eleanor|date=|website=CNN|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Massie was the sole House member to vote against sanctions on [[North Korea]], which the final vote was 419-1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/05/04/house-overwhelmingly-backs-new-sanctions-on-north-korea.html|title=House passes bill to impose new sanctions on North Korea|date=2017-05-04|work=Fox News|access-date=2017-07-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Thomas Massie joined Reps. [[Justin Amash]], [[John Duncan Jr.]] (R-TN) and Sens. [[Rand Paul]] (R-KY) [[Bernie Sanders]] (I-VT) in opposing a bill that would impose new economic sanctions against Russia, Iran, and North Korea. President Trump opposed the bill, pointing out that relations with Russia were already \"at an all-time and dangerous low.\" He did, however, sign the bill though likely out of political pressure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ivn.us/2017/08/03/meet-5-lawmakers-voted-against-russia-sanctions-bill/|title=Meet the 5 Lawmakers Who Voted Against the Russia Sanctions Bill|date=August 3, 2017|website=IVN.us}}</ref>\n\nOn December 29, 2017, Massie voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Tax Cuts and Jobs Act]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=1|website=The New York Times|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> Prior to voting, Massie stated he would support the bill in order to cut taxes, but that he would oppose \"new government spending,\" despite the $1.5 trillion estimated to be added to the [[national debt]] according to the [[Congressional Budget Office]] in wake of the bill being passed.<ref name=\"Marcos111617\">{{cite web|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|last2=Jagoda|first2=Naomi|title=The 13 House Republicans who voted against the GOP tax plan|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/360780-the-13-house-republicans-who-voted-against-the-gop-tax-plan|website=The Hill|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=16 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Ydstie111017\">{{cite web|last1=Ydstie|first1=John|title=GOP Tax Cuts Expected To Push Up Nation's Debt|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/11/10/563314588/gop-tax-cuts-expected-to-push-up-nations-debt|website=National Public Radio|accessdate=28 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018 Massie voted against the Omnibus spending bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/115-2018/h127 |title=H.R. 1625: Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of July 2018 Massie is ranked number 1 in  [[Conservative Review]] Top 25 Conservatives list.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conservativereview.com/top-25/|title=CR TOP 25 CONSERVATIVES}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Government Operations|Subcommittee on Government Operations]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Energy Policy, Health Care and Entitlements|Subcommittee on Energy Policy, Health Care and Entitlements]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Energy|Subcommittee on Energy]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Technology|Subcommittee on Technology]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation|Subcommittee on Aviation]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n==Political positions==\n\n=== Domestic issues ===\n\n==== Education ====\nMassie supports dismantling the [[US Department of Education]]. He supports states making curriculum and funding decisions, as opposed to the federal government. He supports [[school choice]].<ref name=\"Issues\"/>\n\n==== Health care ====\n\nMassie supports the repeal and replacement of the [[Affordable Care Act]] (\"Obamacare\") and describes health care as a \"personal issue\" that \"belongs in the private sector.\" He believes that insurance should be available across state lines and that the insurance industry should be a free market.<ref name=\"Issues\"/>\n\n=== Economic issues ===\n\n==== Budget and economy ====\nMassie describes the economy as \"sluggish.\" He supports auditing the [[US Federal Reserve]].<ref name=\"Issues\">{{cite web|title=Issues|url=https://massie.house.gov/issues|website=Congressman Thomas Massie|accessdate=28 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Jobs ====\n\nMassie says that the country is suffering from \"persistently high unemployment\" \"due to our government's massive debt, over regulation of our businesses, and a  tax system that punishes achievement.\"<ref name=\"Issues\"/>\n\n==== Tax reform ====\n\nMassie supports [[tax reform]] and describes the tax filing process as \"too complicated.\"<ref name=\"Issues\"/>\n\n=== Social issues ===\n\n==== Abortion ====\n\nMassie is [[pro-life]] and believes life begins at conception. He opposes federally funding being used for abortions and supports defunding [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref name=\"Issues\"/>\n\n==== Cannabis ====\n\nMassie has a \"B+\" rating from [[NORML]] for his voting history regarding [[cannabis]]-related causes. Massie supports veterans having access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence. He supports industrial [[hemp]] farming and expanded research into medical marijuana.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Kentucky Scorecard|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/kentucky|website=NORML|accessdate=28 December 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change| title=Kentucky's 4th Congressional district election (2012)<ref>http://elect.ky.gov/SiteCollectionDocuments/Election%20Results/2010-2019/2012/2012genresults.pdf</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Thomas Massie\n  |votes      = 186,036\n  |percentage = 62.13\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = William Adkins\n  |votes      = 104,734\n  |percentage = 34.98\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Independent (politician)\n  |candidate  = David Lewis\n  |votes      = 8,674\n  |percentage = 2.90\n}}\n{{Election box total no change|\n  |votes      = 299,444\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing|\n  |winner    = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin no change| title=Kentucky's 4th Congressional district election (2014)<ref>http://elect.ky.gov/SiteCollectionDocuments/Election%20Results/2010-2019/2014/2014%20General%20Election%20Results.pdf</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Thomas Massie\n  |votes      = 150,464\n  |percentage = 67.73\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Peter Newberry\n  |votes      = 71,694\n  |percentage = 32.27\n}}\n{{Election box total no change|\n  |votes      = 222,158\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing|\n  |winner    = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin no change| title=Kentucky's 4th Congressional district election (2016)<ref>http://elect.ky.gov/results/2010-2019/Documents/2016%20General%20Election%20Results.pdf</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Thomas Massie\n  |votes      = 233,922\n  |percentage = 71.32\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Calvin Sidle\n  |votes      = 94,065\n  |percentage = 28.68\n}}\n{{Election box total no change|\n  |votes      = 327,987\n  |percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing|\n  |winner    = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMassie operates a cattle farm in [[Garrison, Kentucky]] with his wife Rhonda and their four children. They live in a [[solar power|solar-powered]] home that Massie built himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lewiscountyherald.com/4609news.htm |title=Thomas Massie is candidate for judge executive |last=Brown |first=Dennis |accessdate=January 14, 2012 |date=November 17, 2009 |publisher=Lewis County Herald |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621000132/http://lewiscountyherald.com/4609news.htm |archivedate=June 21, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=huang0>{{cite web|url=http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2012/05/17/from-mit-entrepreneur-to-tea-party-leader-the-thomas-massie-story/?single_page=true |title=From MIT Entrepreneur to Tea Party Leader: The Thomas Massie Story |last=Huang |first=Gregory T. |date=May 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 26, 2012 |work=www.xconomy.com}}</ref> He is a Christian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/thomas.massie.31|title=Thomas Massie|publisher=|accessdate=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://massie.house.gov/ Congressman Thomas Massie] official U.S. House site\n* [http://thomasmassie.com Thomas Massie for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Kentucky/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Thomas_Massie_%5BR-4%5D|Thomas Massie}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Thomas Massie}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=M001184 | votesmart=132068 | fec=H2KY04121 | congress=thomas-massie/2094 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Steve Applegate}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[County Judge/Executive|Judge-Executive]] of [[Lewis County, Kentucky|Lewis County]]|years=2011\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=John Patrick Collins}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Kentucky\n| district=4\n| before=[[Geoff Davis]]\n| start=2012\n}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Chairman of the [[Second Amendment Caucus]]}}|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Suzan DelBene]]<br>D-[[Washington (state)|Washington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=242nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Donald Payne Jr.|Donald Payne]]<br>D-[[New Jersey]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{KY-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{USCongRep-start |congresses=112th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Kentucky]]}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/112}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/113}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/114}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Massie, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American gun rights advocates]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Christian libertarians]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United States]]\n[[Category:County judges in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Republicans]]\n[[Category:Lemelson\u2013MI